es what colonization was and looked like on the ground, and how it affected land, water, biota, humans, and the relationship among them, to explain the origins of our built and unbuilt landscapes. Connecting multiple historiographical traditions-history of science and technology, environmental history, social history, and Atlantic history-Candiani proposes that colonization was a class, not an ethnic or nation-based phenomenon, occurring simultaneously on both sides of an Atlantic, where state-building and empire-building were intertwined.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aDrainagexHistoryx17th centuryxMexicoxMexico, Valley of. 0aDrainagezMexicozMexico, Valley ofxHistoryy17th century. 0aFlood controlxHistoryx17th centuryxMexicoxMexico, Valley of. 0aFlood controlzMexicozMexico, Valley ofxHistoryy17th century. 0aHuman ecologyxHistoryx17th centuryxMexicoxMexico, Valley of. 0aHuman ecologyzMexicozMexico, Valley ofxHistoryy17th century. 0aHydraulic engineeringxHistoryx17th centuryxMexicoxMexico, Valley of. 0aHydraulic engineeringzMexicozMexico, Valley ofxHistoryy17th century. 0aLand usezMexicozMexico, Valley ofxHistoryy17th century. 0aPublic worksxHistoryx17th centuryxMexicoxMexico, Valley of. 0aPublic workszMexicozMexico, Valley ofxHistoryy17th century. 4aHistory of hydraulics. 4aMexico City. 4acolonization. 4adrainage projects. 4aearly modern Atlantic. 4aenvironmental change. 4amilitary engineering. 4apublic works. 4arural history. 4aurban history. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804791076zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804791076423Coveruhttps:/